A component = a reusable UI piece with template (HTML) + logic (TypeScript) + styles (CSS).

<pre><code>// delivery-list.component.ts (Standalone — no NgModule!)
@Component({
  selector: 'app-delivery-list',
  standalone: true,
  imports: [CommonModule, TableModule, ButtonModule],
  template: `
    &lt;p-table [value]="deliveries()" [paginator]="true" [rows]="20"&gt;
      &lt;ng-template pTemplate="header"&gt;
        &lt;tr&gt;
          &lt;th&gt;ID&lt;/th&gt;
          &lt;th&gt;Status&lt;/th&gt;
          &lt;th&gt;Driver&lt;/th&gt;
          &lt;th&gt;Scheduled&lt;/th&gt;
        &lt;/tr&gt;
      &lt;/ng-template&gt;
      &lt;ng-template pTemplate="body" let-delivery&gt;
        &lt;tr&gt;
          &lt;td&gt;{{ delivery.id }}&lt;/td&gt;
          &lt;td&gt;&lt;p-tag [severity]="statusSeverity(delivery.status)"&gt;{{ delivery.status }}&lt;/p-tag&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
          &lt;td&gt;{{ delivery.driverName }}&lt;/td&gt;
          &lt;td&gt;{{ delivery.scheduledAt | date:'short' }}&lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;/tr&gt;
      &lt;/ng-template&gt;
    &lt;/p-table&gt;
  `
})
export class DeliveryListComponent {
  private deliveryService = inject(DeliveryService);
  deliveries = signal&lt;Delivery[]&gt;([]);

  ngOnInit() {
    this.deliveryService.findAll().subscribe(data =&gt; this.deliveries.set(data));
  }
}</code></pre>

<strong>Key concepts:</strong>
• <code>standalone: true</code> — modern Angular (no NgModules needed)
• <code>signal&lt;T&gt;</code> — reactive state (Angular 16+, replaces BehaviorSubject)
• <code>inject()</code> — dependency injection (like Spring @Autowired)
• Template uses PrimeNG components (like PrimeFaces for Angular)

Every <code>.subscribe()</code> without cleanup is a potential memory leak.

<pre><code>// ❌ LEAK — subscription lives forever
ngOnInit() {
  this.ws.messages$.subscribe(msg =&gt; this.handle(msg));
}

// ✅ Modern Angular 16+ — takeUntilDestroyed
ngOnInit() {
  this.ws.messages$.pipe(
    takeUntilDestroyed(this.destroyRef)
  ).subscribe(msg =&gt; this.handle(msg));
}

// ✅ Async pipe (auto-subscribes AND unsubscribes)
// Template: {{ deliveries$ | async }}

// ✅ toSignal() — converts Observable to Signal (auto-cleanup)
deliveries = toSignal(this.deliveryService.findAll(), { initialValue: [] });</code></pre>

<strong>Rules:</strong>
• HTTP calls: <strong>no cleanup needed</strong> (they complete after one emission)
• WebSocket/interval/fromEvent: <strong>always cleanup</strong>
• Prefer <code>toSignal()</code> or <code>| async</code> pipe over manual subscribe
• <code>takeUntilDestroyed()</code> is the modern escape hatch

Signals are Angular's answer to React hooks / Vue refs. They provide <strong>fine-grained reactivity</strong> without RxJS complexity.

<pre><code>// Basic signal
const count = signal(0);       // WritableSignal&lt;number&gt;
console.log(count());          // Read: 0
count.set(5);                  // Write: replace value
count.update(v =&gt; v + 1);     // Write: based on current value

// Computed signal (derived state — like a database view)
const doubled = computed(() =&gt; count() * 2);  // auto-tracks dependencies
// doubled() re-evaluates ONLY when count() changes

// Effect (side effect when signal changes)
effect(() =&gt; {
  console.log(`Count changed to ${count()}`);
  // Runs after each change, auto-tracks dependencies
});</code></pre>

<strong>Java parallel:</strong>
• <code>signal()</code> → AtomicReference with change notification
• <code>computed()</code> → a cached getter that invalidates when dependencies change
• <code>effect()</code> → an event listener that fires on state change

Angular uses:
• <strong>Jasmine</strong> — test framework (describe/it/expect) — like JUnit
• <strong>Karma</strong> — test runner — like Maven Surefire
• <strong>TestBed</strong> — DI container for tests — like Spring TestContext

<pre><code>describe('DeliveryService', () =&gt; {
  let service: DeliveryService;
  let httpMock: HttpTestingController;

  beforeEach(() =&gt; {
    TestBed.configureTestingModule({
      providers: [
        provideHttpClient(),
        provideHttpClientTesting()
      ]
    });
    service = TestBed.inject(DeliveryService);
    httpMock = TestBed.inject(HttpTestingController);
  });

  afterEach(() =&gt; httpMock.verify());

  it('should fetch deliveries', () =&gt; {
    const mockData: Delivery[] = [
      { id: 1, status: 'PLANNED', driverName: 'Hans', scheduledAt: '2024-01-15' }
    ];

    service.findAll().subscribe(data =&gt; {
      expect(data.length).toBe(1);
      expect(data[0].driverName).toBe('Hans');
    });

    const req = httpMock.expectOne('/api/v1/deliveries');
    expect(req.request.method).toBe('GET');
    req.flush(mockData);
  });
});</code></pre>
